AR15 Superstudio

Superstudio A was a research studio led by Pier Vittorio Aureli at EPFL, dedicated to the study of the villa as an architectural type from antiquity to the twentieth century. Rather than designing, students close-read a selected case study and produce an Analogous Map: an 80×80cm line drawing that functions as a visual essay, situating a building within its historical, formal and ideological context.

Our group worked on Le Corbusier's villas of the 1920s, exploring the dialectic between his theoretical models - the Maison Dom-Ino and the Maison Citrohan - and their material realisation in built works. Through the analysis of the Villa Stein-de Monzie and the Villa Baizeau, and through the lens of Le Corbusier's own Four Compositions diagram, the essay traces how abstract structural principles found spatial and sensory form. The accompanying text of 1,500 words develops this argument in parallel.